                <alternative value="StatCrunch">
                    <title>StatCrunch Instructions</title>
                    <p>For n = 4 , we know that the result <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>550</m:mn>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math> is not significant. Using the StatCrunch instructions below and
                        starting with n =5 (and going up), create and fill in a table where the
                        column headings are "n," "z (test statistic)," "p-value," and "significant
                        at the 0.05 level (yes/no)." Stop after the first time your result becomes
                        significant at the 0.05 significance level. </p>
                    <p>Here is how you carry out the z-test in StatCrunch:</p>
                    <p>If summaries are given:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose Stat → Z statistics → One sample → with summary</li>
                        <li>Enter Sample mean, standard deviation and sample size.</li>
                        <li>Select Hypothesis Test for μ </li>
                        <li>Select Hypothesis Test</li>
                        <li>Enter a null value and choose the form of the alternative hypothesis
                            from the options not equal, less than, and greater than </li>
                        <li>Check Store in data table </li>

                        <li>Press Compute! </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>If the raw data are given:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose Stat → Z statistics → One sample → with data</li>
                        <li>Select column with sample data</li>
                        <li>Press Next</li>
                        <li>Select Hypothesis Test for μ </li>
                        <li>Enter a null value and choose the form of the alternative hypothesis
                            from the options not equal, less than, and greater than </li>
                        <li>Press Next</li>
                        <li>Check Store in data table </li>
                        <li>Press Compute! </li>
                    </ul>
                </alternative>
                <alternative value="minitab">
                    <title>Minitab Instructions</title>
                    <p>For n = 4, we know that the result <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>550</m:mn>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math> is not significant. Using the Minitab instructions below and
                        starting with n = 5 (and going up), create and fill in a table where the
                        column headings are "n," "z (test statistic)," "p-value," and "significant
                        at the .05 level (yes/no)." Stop after the first time your result becomes
                        significant at the 0.05 significance level. </p>
                    <p>Here is how you carry out the z-test in Minitab:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose: Stat → Basic Statistics → 1-Sample Z</li>
                        <li>If the raw data are given, enter the column name under Samples in
                            columns." If the summaries are given, enter under "Summarized Data" the
                            sample size and sample mean.</li>
                        <li>Enter the known value of the standard deviation (σ).</li>
                        <li>Next to "test mean," enter the null value.</li>
                        <li>Click on "Options" to select the relevant alternative.</li>
                        <li>Click "OK" twice.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Useful Minitab tip: After the first time you run the z-test, it would be
                        useful to use: Edit → Edit Last Dialog.</p>
                </alternative>
                <alternative value="excel">
                    <title>Excel 2013 and 2016 Instructions</title>
                    <p>For n = 4, we know that the result <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>550</m:mn>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math> is not significant. Using the Excel instructions below and
                        starting with n = 5 (and going up), create and fill in a table where the
                        column headings are "n," "z (test statistic)," "p-value," and "significant
                        at the 0.05 level (yes/no)." Stop after the first time your result becomes
                        significant at the 0.05 significance level. </p>
                    <p>To carry out the z-test in Excel, we first need to calculate the z-statistic
                        using the formula <m:math display="inline">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mfrac>
                                    <m:mrow>
                                        <m:mover>
                                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                            <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                        </m:mover>
                                        <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                        <m:msub>
                                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                        </m:msub>
                                    </m:mrow>
                                    <m:mfrac>
                                        <m:mi mathvariant="normal">σ</m:mi>
                                        <m:msqrt>
                                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                                        </m:msqrt>
                                    </m:mfrac>
                                </m:mfrac>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Once you have calculated the z-statistic, you can calculate the p-value
                            using the Excel function <code style="inline">NORM.S.DIST</code>.
                            Remember that in this case, the p-value we want is <code style="inline"
                                >1-NORM.S.DIST(z-statistic)</code>. </li>
                        <li><em>IMPORTANT:</em> Recall that you may use the function <em>NORM.DIST</em> to skip the
                            step of calculating the z-statistic.</li>
                    </ul>
                </alternative>
