                <alternative value="ti">
                    <title>TI Instructions</title>
                    <p>For n = 4 we know that the result <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>550</m:mn>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math> is not significant. </p>
                    <p>Using the TI graphing calculator instructions below and starting with n = 5
                        (and going up), create and fill in a table where the column headings are
                        "n," "z (test statistic)," "p-value," and "significant at the 0.05 level
                        (yes/no)." Stop after the first time your result becomes significant at the
                        0.05 significance level. </p>
                    <p>Note: after conducting the first test with n = 5, your TI will store all the
                        values from this test. Therefore, when you conduct the next text with n = 6,
                        the only change you’ll need to make is to replace the 5 for n with 6. The
                        same is true for the rest of the tests (n = 7, 8, ...). </p>
                    <p><em>One Sample z-test for the mean (&#956;) </em></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose <code style="inline">STAT/TESTS/1:Z-Test </code></li>
                        <li>Note: Use arrows to navigate through the menu. </li>
                        <li>Choose <code style="inline">Stats</code> by using arrows to highlight
                                <code style="inline">Stats</code> then pressing <code style="inline"
                                >ENTER</code>. </li>
                        <li>&#956;<sub>o</sub>: 500 (test population mean from null hypothesis) </li>
                        <li>&#963;: 100 (population standard deviation (this is given in the
                            problem). </li>
                        <li>x-bar: 550 (sample mean) </li>
                        <li>n: 5 (sample size) </li>
                        <li>Choose the relevant form of the alternative hypothesis (&gt;). </li>
                        <li>Arrow down and choose <code style="inline">CALCULATE</code>. </li>
                        <li>You should see: <image style="inline"
